            "replies": [
             {
              "content": "Got it! Let's plan out the new unified interface before implementing. Here's my proposed approach:\n\n```python\ndef python_edit(target_scope: str, code: str, *, insert_before: str = None, insert_after: str = None) -> str:\n    \"\"\"\n    Edit Python code using pytest-style scope syntax.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    - target_scope: str\n        Pytest-style scope identifier, e.g.:\n        - \"file.py\"  (whole file)\n        - \"file.py::MyClass\"  (class)\n        - \"file.py::MyClass::method\"  (method)\n        - \"file.py::MyClass::SubClass::method\"  (nested)\n    \n    - code: str\n        The Python code to insert/replace\n        \n    - insert_before: str = None\n        Where to insert the code. Can be either:\n        - \"__FILE_START__\" (special token for file beginning)\n        - A scope (\"MyClass::method\")\n        - An exact line match\n        \n    - insert_after: str = None\n        Where to insert the code. Can be either:\n        - \"__FILE_END__\" (special token for file end) \n        - A scope (\"MyClass::method\")\n        - An exact line match\n\n    If neither insert_before nor insert_after specified, replaces the node at target_scope.\n    \n    Returns:\n    str: Description of what was modified\n    \"\"\"\n```\n\nThis gives us:\n1. A single unified interface\n2. Simple exact-match line targeting\n3. Special tokens for file start/end\n4. Maintains all existing functionality but with cleaner targeting\n5. Will still handle imports automatically like current version\n\nDoes this API design match what you were envisioning? If so, I can start implementing it. We'll need to:\n\n1. Parse the pytest-style scope syntax\n2. Create appropriate AST visitors\n3. Handle the insert_before/after logic\n4. Maintain import handling\n5. Provide clear error messages for ambiguous/failed matches\n\nWould you like me to proceed with the implementation?",
